\pard\f0\fs28   {\b 46. V. arvensis} L.,{\i  Sp. Pl. }13 (1753). Stem (2-)5-40 cm, simple and erect to much-branched and procumbent, pubescent, and often slightly glandular above. Leaves 2-15 mm, triangular-ovate with truncate or weakly cordate base, crenate-serrate, pubescent or subglabrous, the lower shortly petiolate, the upper sessile. Flowers in racemes; bracts longer than pedicels, the upper lanceolate, the lower ovate. Calyx-segments lanceolate; corolla 2-3 mm in diameter, blue. Capsule c. 3 × 3 mm, obcordate, flat, usually subglabrous except for marginal cilia; style c. 1 mm, scarcely exceeding the sinus. Seeds c. 1 × 0·75 mm, elliptical, flat. 2n = ?14, 16.{\i  Cultivated ground, walls and other dry, open habitats. Almost throughout Europe.} All except Fa Sb; introduced in Is.
\par

\par

\pard\f0\fs28    {\b V. sartoriana} Boiss. & Heldr. in Boiss.,{\i  Diagn. Pl. Or. Nov.}{\b  3}({\b 3}): 171 (1856), is a dwarf plant (c. 5 cm), densely glandular hairy, with longer pedicels, capsule c. 4 mm, and seeds c. 1·2 × 1·0 mm, broadly elliptical and slightly concave on one face. Such plants occur on mountains in Greece and Kriti, but do not seem sufficiently distinct from the very variable{\i  V. arvensis} to merit specific rank.
\par

